That's because the print statement is after the `return` statement, which means that it will never be executed. 

Try moving the `print` statement before the `return` statement, like this:

```python
def index(request):
    courses = Course.objects.all()
    print(courses) # move here
    context = {'courses': courses}
    return render(request, 'index.html', context)
```

This should output the list of courses in the console or terminal when the view is called.

If you are not seeing any output, then it's possible that the `print` statement is being ignored or there is some other issue with the code.

You can try adding some debug information to the template to see if the data is being passed correctly to the view. Here is an example:

```html
{% extends 'index.html' %}

{% block content %}
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Courses</h1>
        {% if courses %}
            <ul>
                {% for course in courses %}
                    <li>{{ course.name }} - {{ course.teacher }}</li>
                {% endfor %}
            </ul>
        {% else %}
            <p>No courses found.</p>
        {% endif %}
    </div>
{% endblock %}
```

This will display a list of courses and teachers, similar to a bullet point list. If you see this output in the browser, then it means that the data is being passed correctly to the template and the issue might be with the CSS or HTML that is causing the elements to not display correctly. 

If you don't see this output, then there may be an issue with how the `views.py` or `models.py` files are defined.

You can also try running the Django server with the `--noreload` flag like this:

```
python manage.py runserver --noreload
```

